<p class="article-lead">A perfume RFQ should make suppliers quote the same project. Include enough detail to expose assumptions without pretending every design decision is already final.</p><h2>Commercial details</h2><ul><li>Destination country, sales channel and target launch window</li><li>Quantity per fragrance and expected repeat-order pattern</li><li>Required quotation currency and Incoterm</li><li>Items that must be priced separately</li></ul><h2>Product details</h2><ul><li>Format, bottle size and concentration direction</li><li>Fragrance brief or existing formula responsibility</li><li>Bottle, pump, cap, decoration, label and carton references</li><li>Required samples, tests, documents and inspection</li></ul><p>Ask the supplier to identify component minimums, buyer-supplied information, exclusions and decisions affecting lead time. A structured RFQ produces a useful comparison and reduces price revisions later.</p>
